2024 Spatial Hackathon Vignette: Image Processing Tools

Set-up

This vignette reflects some of our stretch goals for this Hackathon. Given neighbourhood identification in our previous vignettes, we wondered if it would be possible to integrate our neighbourhoods with H&E information (Aim 2 of this Hackathon). To that end, we developed some functions for image processing.

Preliminary image analysis

In the time given, we were able to achieve the following:

  1. Stain deconvolution
  2. Image gridding and unbiased clustering of Fourier transform spaces

We were unable, in the time allotted, figure out the translation of H&E image coordinates with that of the Xenium-derived cellular coordinates.

Stain deconvolution

Stain deconvolution

Given a H&E image, one early pre-processing step is to separate the image into its H and E components. This is quickly achievable with matrix deconvolution. We use a pseudoinverse (via the MASS package) to ensure a least squares solution.

Entropy is calculated by comparing min-maxxed H and E matrices: i.e. H * log2(H) + E * log2(E).

heList <- heDeconvolve(ima$im)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(as.cimg(ima$im))
Warning: Assuming third dimension corresponds to colour
for(i in 1:length(heList)){
  plot(as.cimg(heList[[i]]), main=names(heList)[i])
}
par(mfrow=c(1,1))

The colours used in deconvolution are as below:

Image tiling and FFT scoring + NMF

The approach herein is based of this paper: PMID: 31855656. Briefly, we tile the images, apply a Hanning window to filter out high frequency noise, and perform a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) to each tile. The frequency component can then be extracted and factorised with Non-Negative Matrix Factorisation (NMF) downstream, to get k anatomical regions.

This approach has the advantage of image analysis without the necessity of training a deep learning model (which requires a large well-annotated corpus to train on).

We did not have time to tune/optimise grid size; though intuitively, grid sizes should be around the size of an anatomical structure of interest (e.g. a lumen). Currently, we arbitrarily create 80 x 80 pixel big tiles, with 50% overlap between tiles.

Tiling and gridding can be done separately for eosin and hematoxylin-deconvolved images (as below):

tf <- tileFFTImage( list('H' = heList$H, 'E' = heList$E) )

We can now plot factor loadings in space. So doing will allow us to identify regions of the H&E image with different H&E structures.

tmp <- list()
for(i in 1:ncol(w)){
  df <- as.data.frame(as.cimg(matrix(w[,i], nrow=dim(tf)[1], ncol=dim(tf)[2])))
  df$NMF <- colnames(w)[i]
  tmp[[i]] <- df
}
tmp <- do.call(rbind, tmp)

ggplot(tmp) +
  geom_raster(aes(x=x, y=y, fill=value)) +
  theme_void(base_size=12) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option='turbo') +
  facet_wrap(~NMF) +
  scale_y_reverse()

It may eventually be possible to see how our cell abundance neighbourhoods (previous vignettes) match up with our tissue architecture neighbourhoods (above); but we did not have time to explore this further.
